```javascript
// Import the required packages
const { Client, Intents, Collection, Permissions } = require('discord.js@14');
const { token } = require('./config.json'); 

const client = new Client({ intents: [Intents.Flags.Guilds, Intents.Flags.GuildMembers, Intents.Flags.GuildBans] });

client.once('ready', async () => {
  console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}!`);
});

const banCommand = new (require('@discordjs/builders').Command)
  .setName('ban')
  .setDescription('Bans a member from the server')
  .setDNSPermissions(Permissions.BanMembers)
  .addUserOption(o => o.setName('user').setDescription('The user to ban').setRequired(true))
  .addStringOption(o => o.setName('reason').setDescription('The reason for ban').setRequired(false));

client.interactions.extend(banCommand, async interaction => {
  const member = interaction.options.getUser('user');
  const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason') || 'No specific reason provided.';

  // Perform a check to ensure the author of the command has ban permissions.
  if (!interaction.memberPermissions.has(Permissions.BanMembers)) {
    return interaction.reply({ content: 'You donHol', ephemeral: true });
  }

  // Confirm the ban action through a follow-up message.
  const confirmation = await interaction.followUp({ content: `Are you sure you want to ban ${member.tag} (ID: ${member.id}) for the reason: \`${reason}\`?` });

  await member.ban({ reason }).then(
    async () => {
      await confirmation.edit(`Successfully banned ${member.tag} (ID: ${member.id}). Reason: \`${reason}\`.`),
      interaction.guild.channels.cache.get('YOUR_AUDIT_LOG_CHANNEL_ID').wpin() // Optional: move focus to audit log
    }
  ).catch(console.error); 

  // Logging and other logic goes here...
});

client.login(token);
```

Here's a breakdown of key points in the above code:

- It uses the latest Discord.js (v14), extends slash commands interactively, and verifies the member banning with appropriate permissions check.
- It includes an optional reason for banning.
- It sends an interactive confirmation before actually performing the ban. 

Make sure you replace `'YOUR_AUDIT_LOG_CHANNEL_ID'` with your actual channel ID where you'd like to announce banned users. Also, ensure you've handled unhandled rejections & logged the complete interaction for a secure production-level bot. 

Lastly, don't forget to register the command in Discord Developer Portal and grant Discord Bot Application the necessary permissions over the guild. The permission for banning members is implicit with the returned permission structure from Discord.js v14 Intents & Permissions model.

